WITH MOVE SEMANTICS
---------------------------------------------------------

class Buffer
{
    int* data;
    int size;

public:
    Buffer(int n)
    {
        size = n;
        data = new int[size];
    }

    // Copy Constructor
    Buffer(const Buffer& other)
    {
        size = other.size;
        data = new int[size];

        for (int i = 0; i < size; i++)
            data[i] = other.data[i];

        cout << "Copy Constructor\n";
    }

    // Move Constructor
    Buffer(Buffer&& other)
    {
        data = other.data;
        size = other.size;

        other.data = nullptr;
        other.size = 0;

        cout << "Move Constructor\n";
    }

    ~Buffer()
    {
        delete[] data;
    }
};

Usage:

Buffer b1(1000000);
Buffer b2 = std::move(b1);

Before Move:

b1 ----> [1M integers]
b2 ----> nullptr

After Move:

b1 ----> nullptr
b2 ----> [1M integers]

No new allocation.
No element copying.

Only pointer transfer.

Complexity:
O(1)

---------------------------------------------------------
What Improved After Move?
---------------------------------------------------------

Without Move:
✓ Allocate new memory
✓ Copy all elements
✓ More CPU usage
✓ More memory usage
✓ O(n)

With Move:
✓ No new allocation
✓ No element copying
✓ Transfer ownership only
✓ Less CPU usage
✓ Less memory usage
✓ O(1)

