Move semantics improve performance by transferring ownership
of resources (heap memory, buffers, file handles, etc.)
instead of performing expensive deep copies.

********WHAT TO EXPLAIN IN ABOVE CODE***
=========================================================
What to Explain in Interview (Buffer Class + Move Semantics)
=========================================================

1. Buffer is a resource-owning class.
   - It owns dynamically allocated heap memory (int* data).
   - The actual array is stored on the heap.

   Buffer b1(1000000);

   b1
   +-------+      +-----------------------+
   | data  | ---> | 1M integers on heap   |
   +-------+      +-----------------------+

---------------------------------------------------------

2. Without Move Semantics (Deep Copy)

   Buffer b2 = b1;

   What happens?
   - Allocate another array of 1M integers.
   - Copy all 1M elements.
   - Two separate arrays exist.

   Memory:

   b1 ---> [1M integers]
   b2 ---> [1M integers]

   Cost:
   - Extra memory allocation
   - Copy of all elements
   - High CPU usage
   - O(n) complexity

---------------------------------------------------------

3. What is the Problem?

   If b1 is no longer needed, creating another 1M-element array
   is wasteful.

   We do not need two copies of the same data.

   This is called unnecessary duplication.

---------------------------------------------------------

4. With Move Semantics

   Buffer b2 = std::move(b1);

   Move Constructor:

   data = other.data;
   size = other.size;

   other.data = nullptr;
   other.size = 0;

   What happens?
   - No new memory allocation.
   - No copying of 1M integers.
   - Ownership of the pointer is transferred.

   Before Move:

   b1 ---> [1M integers]
   b2 ---> nullptr

   After Move:

   b1 ---> nullptr
   b2 ---> [1M integers]

---------------------------------------------------------

5. Improvements After Move

   Without Move:
   ✓ Allocate new memory
   ✓ Copy all elements
   ✓ Higher CPU usage
   ✓ Higher memory usage
   ✓ O(n)

   With Move:
   ✓ No new allocation
   ✓ No element copying
   ✓ Transfer ownership only
   ✓ Lower CPU usage
   ✓ Lower memory usage
   ✓ O(1)

---------------------------------------------------------

Interview One-Liner:

"This class demonstrates why move semantics were introduced in
C++11. Deep copying large resources is expensive (O(n)).
Move semantics transfer ownership of the resource by stealing
the pointer, avoiding allocation and copying, making the
