3. What Move Semantics Solves?
------------------------------
- Eliminates unnecessary deep copies
- Transfers ownership of resources
- Improves performance significantly
- Essential for modern STL efficiency

-----------------------------------------

4. Core Idea
------------
Instead of:
- Copying data from source → destination

We do:
- Transfer pointer/resource ownership
- Nullify source

-----------------------------------------

5. Copy vs Move  ***********
---------------
COPY:
- Duplicates resource
- Both objects own separate memory

MOVE:
- Transfers resource
- Source becomes empty but valid

-----------------------------------------

6. Example Without Move (Copy)
-----------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    vector<int> v1(5, 10);

    vector<int> v2 = v1;  // COPY (expensive)

    cout << v1.size();  // still 5
}

-----------------------------------------

7. Move Semantics Example
-------------------------
#include <iostream>
#include <vector>
using namespace std;

int main() {
    vector<int> v1(5, 10);

    vector<int> v2 = std::move(v1);  // MOVE

    cout << v1.size(); // 0 (or valid but unspecified state)
}

-----------------------------------------

8. std::move (Important)************
------------------------
- std::move does NOT move anything.
- It converts lvalue → rvalue reference.
- It enables move constructor / move assignment.

Example:
int a = 10;
int b = std::move(a); // treats a as rvalue

-----------------------------------------

9. Move Constructor
-------------------
- Special constructor that steals resources.

Example:

class MyString {
    char* data;

public:
    MyString(char* s) {
        data = s;
    }

    // COPY constructor
    MyString(const MyString& other) {
        data = new char[strlen(other.data) + 1];
        strcpy(data, other.data);
    }

    // MOVE constructor
    MyString(MyString&& other) noexcept {
        data = other.data;      // steal pointer
        other.data = nullptr;   // leave source safe
    }
};

-----------------------------------------

10. Move Assignment Operator
---------------------------
MyString& operator=(MyString&& other) noexcept {
    if (this != &other) {
        delete[] data;        // release old resource
        data = other.data;    // steal
        other.data = nullptr;
    }
    return *this;
}

-----------------------------------------

11. Key Rules of Move Semantics
------------------------------
- Only works with rvalues (temporary objects)
- Source object must remain valid but unspecified
- After move, source should be safe to destroy
- Should use noexcept for performance (STL optimization)

-----------------------------------------

12. When Move Happens Automatically?
-----------------------------------
- Returning local objects from function
- Using std::move explicitly
- Temporary objects

Example:
vector<int> createVector() {
    vector<int> v(1000);
    return v;   // move optimization (RVO/NRVO)
}

-----------------------------------------

13. Move vs Copy Summary
------------------------
COPY:
- Expensive
- Duplicates memory
- Safe but slow

MOVE:
- Fast
- Transfers ownership
- Efficient for large objects

-----------------------------------------

14. Real-world Usage
--------------------
- std::vector
- std::string
- std::map / std::unordered_map
- Smart pointers (std::unique_ptr)
- Returning objects from functions

-----------------------------------------

15. Interview Key Points
------------------------
- Introduced in C++11
- Uses rvalue references (&&)
- std::move enables move semantics
- Move constructor + move assignment operator
- Solves performance issues of deep copying
- Improves STL efficiency dramatically

